<h2>What is Chapel?</h2>

<p>Chapel is a modern programming language that is...<br>
<ul>
<li> <b>parallel:</b> contains first-class concepts for concurrent and parallel computation<br>
<li> <b>productive:</b> designed with programmability and performance in mind<br>
<li> <b>portable:</b> runs on laptops, clusters, the cloud, and HPC systems<br>
<li> <b>scalable:</b> supports locality-oriented features for distributed memory systems<br>
<li> <b>open-source:</b> hosted on <a href = "https://github.com/chapel-lang/">GitHub</a>, permissively <a href = "license.html">licensed</a><br>
</ul>


<h2>New to Chapel?</h2>

As an introduction to Chapel, you may want to...<br>

<ul>
  <li> read a <a href =
                        "http://www.cray.com/blog/chapel-productive-parallel-programming/">blog
                        article</a> or <a href =
                        "publications/PMfPC-Chapel.pdf">book
                        chapter</a></li>

  <li> watch <a href = "https://youtu.be/0DjIdRJIqRY">an overview
                        talk</a> or browse its <a href =
                        "presentations/ChapelForATPESC2016-presented.pdf">slides</a>

  <li> <a href = "download.html">download</a> the release
                        
  <li> browse <a href = "docs/latest/examples/index.html">sample
                        programs</a>

  <li> view <a href = "learning.html">other resources</a> to learn
                        how to trivially write distributed programs
                        like this:</li>

  <p>
    <div class="code-snippet">
      <pre class="code">
<b>use</b> CyclicDist;               <i>// use the Cyclic distribution library</i>
<b>config const</b> n = 100;         <i>// use</i> ./a.out --n=&lt;val&gt; <i>to override this default</i>

<b>forall</b> i <b>in</b> {1..n} <b>dmapped</b> Cyclic(startIdx=1) <b>do</b>
  writeln("Hello from iteration ", i, " of ", n, " running on node ", <b>here</b>.id);</pre>
    </div>
  </p>

</ul>
    


